.SH NAME
AbstractRange \- AbstractRange
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]AbstractRange\f[B]\f[R] abstract interface is the base
class upon which all DOM range types are defined.
A \f[B]range\f[R] is an object that indicates the start and end points
of a section of content within the document.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] As an abstract interface, you will not directly
instantiate an object of type \f[CR]AbstractRange\f[R].
Instead, you will use the \f[CR]Range\f[R] or \f[CR]StaticRange\f[R]
interfaces.
To understand the difference between those two interfaces, and how to
choose which is appropriate for your needs, consult each interface\[cq]s
documentation.
.RE
.SH INSTANCE PROPERTIES
.TP
\f[B]collapsed\f[R] \f[I](read\-only)\f[R]
A Boolean value which is \f[CR]true\f[R] if the range is
\f[I]collapsed\f[R].
A collapsed range is a range whose start position and end position are
the same, resulting in a zero\-character\-long range.
.TP
\f[B]endContainer\f[R] \f[I](read\-only)\f[R]
The \f[CR]Node\f[R] object in which the end of the range, as specified
by the \f[CR]endOffset\f[R] property, is located.
.TP
\f[B]endOffset\f[R] \f[I](read\-only)\f[R]
An integer value indicating the offset, in characters, from the
beginning of the node\[cq]s contents to the last character of the range
represented by the range object.
This value must be less than the length of the \f[CR]endContainer\f[R]
node.
.TP
\f[B]startContainer\f[R] \f[I](read\-only)\f[R]
The DOM \f[CR]Node\f[R] in which the beginning of the range, as
specified by the \f[CR]startOffset\f[R] property, is located.
.TP
\f[B]startOffset\f[R] \f[I](read\-only)\f[R]
An integer value indicating the offset, in characters, from the
beginning of the node\[cq]s contents to the first character of the
contents referred to by the range object.
This value must be less than the length of the node indicated in
\f[CR]startContainer\f[R].
.SH INSTANCE METHODS
\f[I]The \f[CI]AbstractRange\f[I] interface doesn\[cq]t provide any
methods.\f[R]
.SH USAGE NOTES
.SS Range types
All ranges of content within a \f[CR]document\f[R] are described using
instances of interfaces based on \f[CR]AbstractRange\f[R].
There are two such interfaces:
.TP
\f[B]Range\f[R]
The \f[CR]Range\f[R] interface has been around for a long time and has
only recently been redefined to be based upon \f[CR]AbstractRange\f[R]
as the need arose to define other forms of range data.
\f[CR]Range\f[R] provides methods that allow you to alter the
range\[cq]s endpoints, as well as methods to compare ranges, detect
intersections between ranges, and so forth.
.TP
\f[B]StaticRange\f[R]
A \f[CR]StaticRange\f[R] is a basic range which cannot be changed once
it\[cq]s been created.
Specifically, as the node tree mutates and changes, the range does not.
This is useful when you need to specify a range that will only be used
once, since it avoids the performance and resource impact of the more
complex \f[CR]Range\f[R] interface.
.SS Contents of elements
When trying to access the contents of an element, keep in mind that the
element itself is a node, but so is any text inside it.
In order to set a range endpoint within the text of an element, be sure
to find the text node inside the element:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] startElem = document.querySelector(\[dq]p\[dq]);
\f[B]const\f[R] endElem = startElem.querySelector(\[dq]span\[dq]);
\f[B]const\f[R] range = document.createRange();

range.setStart(startElem, 0);
range.setEnd(endElem, endElem.childNodes[0].length / 2);
\f[B]const\f[R] contents = range.cloneContents();

document.body.appendChild(contents);
.EE
.PP
This example creates a new range, \f[CR]range\f[R], and sets its
starting point to the third child node of the first element.
The end point is set to be the middle of the first child of the span,
and then the range is used to copy the contents of the range.
.SS Ranges and the hierarchy of the DOM
In order to define a range of characters within a document in a way that
is able to span across zero or more node boundaries, and which is as
resilient as possible to changes to the DOM, you can\[cq]t specify the
offset to the first and last characters in the HTML.
There are a few good reasons for that.
.PP
First, after your page is loaded, the browser isn\[cq]t thinking in
terms of HTML.
Once it\[cq]s been loaded, the page is a tree of DOM \f[CR]Node\f[R]
objects, so you need to specify the beginning and ending locations of a
range in terms of nodes and positions within nodes.
.PP
Second, in order to support the mutability of the DOM tree as much as
possible, you need a way to represent positions relative to nodes in the
tree, rather than global positions within the entire document.
By defining points within the document as offsets within a given node,
those positions remain consistent with the content even as nodes are
added to, removed from, or moved around within the DOM tree\[em]within
reason.
There are fairly obvious limitations (such as if a node is moved to be
after the endpoint of a range, or if the content of a node is heavily
altered), but it\[cq]s far better than nothing.
.PP
Third, using node\-relative positions to define the start and end
positions will generally be easier to make perform well.
Rather than having to negotiate the DOM figuring out what your global
offset refers to, the user agent (browser) can instead go directly to
the node indicated by the starting position and start from there,
working its way forward until it reaches the given offset into the
ending node.
.PP
To illustrate this, consider the HTML below:
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]div\f[R] class=\[dq]container\[dq]>
  <\f[B]div\f[R] class=\[dq]header\[dq]>
    <\f[B]img\f[R] src=\[dq]\[dq] class=\[dq]sitelogo\[dq] />
    <\f[B]h1\f[R]>The Ultimate Website</\f[B]h1\f[R]>
  </\f[B]div\f[R]>
  <\f[B]article\f[R]>
    <\f[B]section\f[R] class=\[dq]entry\[dq] id=\[dq]entry1\[dq]>
      <\f[B]h2\f[R]>Section 1: An interesting thing\&...</\f[B]h2\f[R]>
      <\f[B]p\f[R]>A <\f[B]em\f[R]>very</\f[B]em\f[R]> interesting thing happened on the way to the forum\&...</\f[B]p\f[R]>
      <\f[B]aside\f[R] class=\[dq]callout\[dq]>
        <\f[B]h2\f[R]>Aside</\f[B]h2\f[R]>
        <\f[B]p\f[R]>An interesting aside to share with you\&...</\f[B]p\f[R]>
      </\f[B]aside\f[R]>
    </\f[B]section\f[R]>
  </\f[B]article\f[R]>
  <\f[B]pre\f[R] id=\[dq]log\[dq]></\f[B]pre\f[R]>
</\f[B]div\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
