.PP
If you want to create a range that incorporates the contents of the
\f[CR]<p>\f[R] element whose contents are
\f[CR]\[dq]A <em>very</em> interesting thing happened on the way to the forum\&...\[dq]\f[R],
you can do so like this:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] pRange = document.createRange();
pRange.selectNodeContents(document.querySelector(\[dq]#entry1 p\[dq]));
.EE
.PP
Since we wish to select the entire contents of the \f[CR]<p>\f[R]
element, including its descendants, this works perfectly.
.PP
If we wish to instead copy the text \[lq]An interesting thing\&...\[rq]
from the \f[CR]<section>\f[R]\[cq]s heading (an \f[CR]h2\f[R] element)
through the end of the letters \[lq]ve\[rq] in the \f[CR]<em>\f[R]
within the paragraph below it, the following code would work:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] range = document.createRange();
\f[B]const\f[R] startNode = document.querySelector(\[dq]section h2\[dq]).childNodes[0];
range.setStart(startNode, 11);

\f[B]const\f[R] endNode = document.querySelector(\[dq]#entry1 p em\[dq]).childNodes[0];
range.setEnd(endNode, 2);

\f[B]const\f[R] fragment = range.cloneContents();
.EE
.PP
Here an interesting problem arises\[em]we are capturing content from
multiple nodes located at different levels of the DOM hierarchy, and
then only part of one of them.
What should the result look like?
.PP
As it turns out, the DOM specification fortunately addresses this exact
issue.
For example, in this case, we\[cq]re calling \f[CR]cloneContents()\f[R]
on the range to create a new \f[CR]DocumentFragment\f[R] object
providing a DOM subtree which replicates the contents of the specified
range.
To do this, \f[CR]cloneContents()\f[R] constructs all the nodes needed
to preserve the structure of the indicated range, but no more than
necessary.
.PP
In this example, the start of the specified range is found within the
text node below the section\[cq]s heading, which means that the new
\f[CR]DocumentFragment\f[R] will need to contain an \f[CR]h2\f[R] and,
below it, a text node.
.PP
The range\[cq]s end is located below the \f[CR]<p>\f[R] element, so that
will be needed within the new fragment.
So will the text node containing the word \[lq]A\[rq], since that\[cq]s
included in the range.
Finally, an \f[CR]<em>\f[R] and a text node below it will be added below
the \f[CR]<p>\f[R] as well.
.PP
The contents of the text nodes are then determined by the offsets into
those text nodes given when calling \f[CR]setStart()\f[R] and
\f[CR]setEnd()\f[R].
Given the offset of 11 into the heading\[cq]s text, that node will
contain \[lq]An interesting thing\&...\[rq].
Similarly, the last text node will contain \[lq]ve\[rq], given the
request for the first two characters of the ending node.
.PP
