.SH EXAMPLE
Consider this simple HTML fragment of HTML.
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]p\f[R]><\f[B]strong\f[R]>This</\f[B]strong\f[R]> is a paragraph.</\f[B]p\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
Imagine using a \f[CR]Range\f[R] to extract the word \[lq]paragraph\[rq]
from this.
The code to do that looks like the following:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] paraNode = document.querySelector(\[dq]p\[dq]);
\f[B]const\f[R] paraTextNode = paraNode.childNodes[1];

\f[B]const\f[R] range = document.createRange();
range.setStart(paraTextNode, 6);
range.setEnd(paraTextNode, paraTextNode.length \- 1);

\f[B]const\f[R] fragment = range.cloneContents();
document.body.appendChild(fragment);
.EE
.PP
First we get references to the paragraph node itself as well as to the
\f[I]second\f[R] child node within the paragraph.
The first child is the \f[CR]<strong>\f[R] element.
The second child is the text node \[rq] is a paragraph.\[rq].
.PP
With the text node reference in hand, we create a new \f[CR]Range\f[R]
object by calling \f[CR]createRange()\f[R] on the \f[CR]Document\f[R]
itself.
We set the starting position of the range to the sixth character of the
text node\[cq]s string, and the end position to the length of the text
node\[cq]s string minus one.
This sets the range to encompass the word \[lq]paragraph\[rq].
.PP
We then finish up by calling \f[CR]cloneContents()\f[R] on the
\f[CR]Range\f[R] to create a new \f[CR]DocumentFragment\f[R] object
which contains the portion of the document encompassed by the range.
After that, we use \f[CR]appendChild()\f[R] to add that fragment at the
end of the document\[cq]s body, as obtained from
\f[CR]document.body\f[R].
.PP
